<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: ARLETA; MAN FOUND STABBED DIES FROM WOUNDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A man who had been stabbed several times while sitting in his car was 
discovered by teen-agers early Tuesday who originally thought the man's body 
was a Halloween prank, Los Angeles police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Leopoldo Yerena, 42, of Arleta, died at Holy Cross Medical Center, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Three youths, who were driving in the area about 1 a.m., found Yerena sitting 
behind the steering wheel of a parked car in the 10200 block of Vena Avenue 
near Van Nuys Boulevard, said LAPD Detective Frank Bishop. 
</P>
<P>
 "At first they thought (the body) was a dummy, some Halloween prank," Bishop 
said. "But after they saw all the blood, they weren't sure and called police." 
</P>
<P>
 Detectives have no leads. "We don't know why he was sitting there," Bishop 
said. "We don't know who did it. There were no witnesses." TIMOTHY WILLIAMS 
</P>
