<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: LAGUNA NIGUEL; TEEN CENTER TO OFFER MUSIC, REFRESHMENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Local residents have some good news for teen-agers bored with staying home and 
watching movies or driving out of town for fun on a Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
 They plan to open a "teen center" on Saturdays from 8 p.m. to midnight that 
would offer refreshments and live music in a coffeehouse atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
 The free teen parties -- which organizers hope to begin this Saturday -- will 
be held at Shepherd of the Hills Church, 30121 Niguel Road. The center's 
advisory group is still seeking donations of tables, sound and lighting 
equipment and refreshment supplies to get the gatherings started. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's a need here. There's nothing available in terms of a teen hangout of 
any kind," said the church's pastor, Huw Anwyl. 
</P>
<P>
 Youths between the ages of 12 and 17 are invited to participate. Organizers 
are looking for young local bands that would like to provide the entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
 "A lot of kids have athletics they can be part of, but a lot of kids don't," 
said the Rev. Jack Hennings of Faith Community Episcopal Church, who helped 
organize the Saturday night get-togethers. "I have a teen-ager myself, and I 
realize it's important for there to be a place where they can go. I appreciate 
that they go to the malls and hang out, but that only gives so much to 
developing themselves." 
</P>
<P>
 Hennings said that local service groups such as the Rotary Club have pledged 
their support. The events will be chaperoned, and sheriff's deputies have 
promised to patrol the area. LYNN FRANEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
