<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV RATINGS; 'CHICAGO HOPE' IS REVIVED BY 'MURDER'S' GET-WELL SLOT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEE MARGULIES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 CBS' "Chicago Hope" got crushed by NBC's "ER" in the Thursday-night battle of 
medical dramas this fall, but it turns out that it was nothing personal. 
Millions of viewers were only too happy to take a look when CBS put the series 
on at a more convenient hour last Sunday--namely, into the slot normally 
occupied by "Murder, She Wrote." 
</P>
<P>
 Ratings released Tuesday by the A.C. Nielsen Co. showed that "Chicago Hope," 
co-starring Adam Arkin, ranked No. 10 among the 93 network programs in prime 
time last week. Indeed, it was the most-watched medical drama of the week ("ER" 
wasn't on). CBS hopes the people who watched on Sunday will now stickwith the 
series in its regular time slot of Thursday at 9 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, "Home Improvement," after being displaced for a week, returned to 
its position atop the national ratings list. It was one of six ABC shows in the 
Top 10, a showing that helped propel the network well ahead of its competitors. 
</P>
<P>
 The annual Halloween episode of "The Simpsons" gave the cartoon series its 
best ratings since Fox moved it back to Sundays at 8 p.m. this fall (No. 27), 
and a "Simpsons" rerun at 8:30 did even better (No. 22). Southland Ratings 
