<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOT LINE SET UP TO STEM MINORITY VOTER THREATS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SAM FULWOOD III, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Aiming to prevent efforts to intimidate minority voters from casting ballots 
in next week's midterm elections, a coalition of civil rights organizations 
Tuesday announced a new information hot line to field questions and complaints 
about poll issues. 
</P>
<P>
 "Over the past 13 years, harassment and intimidation have followed minority 
voters to the polls, especially when close races are predicted," said Wade 
Henderson, Washington director of the National Assn. for the Advancement of 
Colored People, which is supervising the hot line. "We are concerned once again 
that these issues will have to be addressed in 1994 for this expected close 
election." 
</P>
<P>
 The hot line -- 1-800-775-VOTE -- opened for calls late Tuesday and will 
remain active until Election Day. It is an attempt by voting rights activists 
and civil rights organizations to combat "dirty tricks," which they claim have 
been used by the GOP to inhibit minorities from voting. The GOP vigorously 
denied the charges. 
</P>
<P>
 In recent years, Democrats have charged GOP activists with sending minority 
voters bogus warnings about voter credentials immediately before close 
elections. Some civil libertarians charged that such targeted warnings were 
designed to scare off minority voters, who tend to vote for Democratic 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
 Members representing the coalition -- including the Rev. Jesse Jackson's 
Rainbow Coalition, National Council of La Raza, Mexican American Legal Defense 
and Educational Fund, National Political Congress of Black Women, Coalition of 
Black Trade Unionists and other organizations -- have agreed to encourage their 
supporters to watch for pre-election and vote-day activities that might prevent 
minorities from voting. 
</P>
<P>
 In response to the creation of the hot line, the Justice Department announced 
that it would send more than 200 federal observers to monitor polling places in 
11 states covered by the Voting Rights Act of 1965. The specific sites will be 
announced next week. The department has had such monitors for many years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
